{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 18:58:10.572323", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and actions taken\n- Verified end-to-end reachability from user hosts to server farm using multi-host ping matrix.\n- Checked HTTP service behavior via repeated curl timing tests from two representative hosts to the load balancer VIP (web99.local) and to a direct web server (web0.local).\n- Inspected service listening sockets on the load balancer and all four web servers.\n- Validated OSPF adjacencies and routing tables on key routing nodes (server_access_router, router_core_1, router_dist_1_1).\n- Confirmed host network configuration (addressing, default gateway, DNS resolver).\n\nKey observations\n1) IP reachability\n- All tested hosts can reach web_server_0 (10.200.0.3) and web_server_1 (10.200.0.4) with 0% packet loss; typical RTTs ~1.5–3.5 ms.\n- Load balancer and inter-server reachability also succeed. Some intra–server-farm pings (e.g., web_server_1 <-> web_server_0, and load_balancer -> servers) show higher jitter than others but remain low in absolute latency.\n\n2) HTTP service availability/performance\n- load_balancer is listening on TCP/80; each web_server_0..3 is listening on TCP/80.\n- HTTP access to web99.local from hosts consistently succeeds:\n  - Name lookup: ~2–6 ms\n  - TCP connect: ~4–11 ms\n  - TTFB: ~0.21–0.34 s\n  - Total time: ~1.02–1.13 s\n- Direct HTTP access to web0.local from a host also succeeds with similar timing. The gap between TTFB (~0.2–0.3 s) and total (~1.0 s) suggests normal payload transfer time rather than a network stall.\n\n3) Routing/OSPF\n- OSPF adjacencies:\n  - server_access_router is Full with router_core_3 (consistent with topology).\n  - router_core_1 is Full with core peers and both distribution routers.\n  - router_dist_1_1 is Full with router_core_1. No adjacency flaps observed; Dead/Up timers look healthy.\n- Routing tables are consistent:\n  - server_access_router advertises 10.200.0.0/24 as directly connected and has OSPF-learned routes to all host subnets via core.\n  - router_core_1 learns 10.200.0.0/24 via core3, and learns host subnets correctly via distribution.\n  - router_dist_1_1 has 10.1.1.0/24 connected and learns server farm and other infrastructure subnets upstream via core1.\n\n4) Host configuration\n- Hosts have DHCP-acquired addressing and valid default gateways (10.1.1.1 and 10.2.1.1) and resolv.conf pointing to the correct DNS server (10.200.0.2).\n- DHCP leases on the sampled hosts show very short remaining lifetimes (~30–35 seconds at time of check), which is unusual but not directly causing reachability issues in the current tests.\n\nAnomalies detected\n- Minor RTT jitter for certain intra–server-farm pings (notably between web_server_0 and web_server_1 and from load_balancer to web servers). Absolute latency is low and no loss is observed; this presents as variability rather than a fault.\n- Very short DHCP lease lifetimes observed on hosts (tens of seconds remaining). This is atypically short for enterprise environments and could lead to frequent renewals, though no immediate impact was observed in current tests.\n\nLocalization of potential issues\n- Jitter is localized to the server farm segment (10.200.0.0/24), particularly traffic involving web_server_0 and web_server_1 and the load_balancer to servers. It does not appear on host-to-server paths consistently and is not accompanied by loss.\n- The short DHCP lease timer is localized to the DHCP service configuration (central DHCP server or relay-induced policy), not to network transport.\n\nLikely root causes (inferred)\n- Intra–server-farm jitter: Likely due to server-side or virtualization/container scheduling variability on the server access segment rather than routing or switching faults; OSPF and routes are clean, and no loss is present.\n- Short DHCP lease times: Likely a configuration choice on the DHCP server (very short lease duration); network transport/relay appears to be functioning correctly since hosts have valid leases and connectivity.\n\nOverall assessment\n- Core-to-distribution-to-access routing is healthy; OSPF adjacencies are established and stable; routes are correct and consistent with the topology.\n- DNS resolution and HTTP application access to both the load balancer VIP (web99.local) and direct web servers are successful with consistent timing.\n- No critical faults affecting end-to-end service delivery are detected at this time. The noted minor anomalies do not currently impair availability or basic performance.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 13068, "output_tokens": 4130, "total_tokens": 17198, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 7552}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3072}}}
